Schools encouraged to focus more on math, spelling and grammar
In English literature courses, students will have to cover at least one play by Shakespeare, a 19th-century novel, romantic poetry and contemporary British novels from 1914 onwards.
"Unseen texts" are also included in the exam in order to encourage broader reading.
The combined course of English literature and language will be abolished.
As of 2015, students will be required to take a stand-alone GCSE language exam, with strong incentives to choose English literature as a separate qualification.
The Ministry of Education will publish tomorrow the new curricula for English and mathematics – the first subjects that have been radically redesigned.
Other core subjects will be changed next year.
In a separate initiative, Ofqual, the exam regulator, will announce a reorganization of GCSE structures, including a new grading system and less coursework.
In a speech in the summer, Education Secretary Michael Gove said there was a "broad consensus that we need to reform our exam system to restore public confidence," stressing that GCSEs would become "more challenging, ambitious and rigorous."
Studies show that English schools spend less time on maths – 116 hours per year or three hours per week per school year – than most other countries.
In contrast, Australian schools teach an average of 143 hours per year and students in Singapore receive 138 hours.
While there will be no formal requirement to allow more time for math in the timetable, coalition sources say the comprehensive math exam – combined with a stronger emphasis on the subject in rankings – will likely encourage schools to schedule more hours.
The curriculum pays more attention to "real-life problems," including financial mathematics.
