Intelligence whistleblower Edward Snowden is basically willing to talk to German authorities.
First, however, he wants to have his situation clarified.
This was made clear by the former NSA employee wanted by the US in an unaddressed letter, which the Green politician Hans-Christian Ströbele published on Friday after a meeting with Snowden and forwarded to the Federal Government, the Bundestag and the Federal Prosecutor General.
According to a translation distributed by Ströbele, the letter reads as follows:
To the responsible persons
I have been asked to write to you regarding your investigation into mass surveillance.
My name is Edward Joseph Snowden and I used to work as a technical expert with the National Security Agency (NSA), the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA) of the United States.
In the course of my employment in these institutions, I witnessed systematic violations of the law by my government, which led me to act out of moral duty.
As a result of the publication of these concerns, I faced a serious and ongoing incitement that forced me to leave my family and my homeland.
I am currently living in exile and enjoy temporary asylum granted to me by the Russian Federation in accordance with international law.
I am encouraged by the response to my political actions, both in the US and elsewhere.
Citizens around the world, as well as high officials – including the United States – have judged the revelations of an all-encompassing surveillance system accountable to no one as a service to the public.
These espionage revelations led to many proposals for new laws and policies aimed at the previously covert abuse of public trust.
The benefits to society from these lessons learned are becoming increasingly clear; at the same time, the risks accepted were visibly reduced.
Although the outcome of my efforts has been demonstrably positive, my administration continues to treat dissent as a breach of loyalty and seeks to criminalize and prosecute political expression.
Nevertheless, speaking the truth is not a crime.
I am confident that the United States government, with the support of the international community, will abandon this detrimental attitude.
I hope that, once the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved, I will be able to participate appropriately and lawfully in clarifying the facts of the statements made in the media, particularly with regard to the truth and authenticity of the reports.
I look forward to talking to you in your country once the situation is resolved and thank you for your efforts to uphold the international law that protects us all.
Edward Snowden witnessed by Hans-Christian Ströbele
