Journey through mud, rivers, and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical aid to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend nearly every weekend treating hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for 5,000 people.
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 "CNN Heroes of 2013".
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to vote him "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue their extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but then inflammation formed that spread to his brain, causing a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," says Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," comments Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be first, and yet you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for every 413 people.
But even if there were a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of the country's healthcare expenditure is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer made Bwelle decide to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and worked as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and provides free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and drive with the tied medical equipment on the roof over dirt terrain to the villages that need help.
Things don't always go smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed like heroes: a feast, song and dance and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and Bwelle – with his big smile and boundless energy – likes to be part of the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team begins examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village – and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates — a document required for school, but many poor families simply can't afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, the town hall or an apartment; After the procedure, patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operating room and the disinfection equipment is fed by the group's generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It's a strenuous workload, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work," says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has performed 700 free surgeries in the last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference to the people it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a hernia he had received now allowed him to return to work.
"This changes the future of my family," the man said.
In addition to weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his charitable work, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," says Katie O'Malley, who is in her sophomore year at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteers in Bwelle's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain hands-on experience they would never get at home.
"We can be present at surgeries where we help dab blood or mistake the instruments for Dr. Bwelle," O'Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes care of the accommodation, transport and guidance.
"He's a hero without a doubt," says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others live happier lives and fulfilling a promise he made to his father brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy doing this work," says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
Pope Francis appoints first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will appoint new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time on February 22, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the pope, and they are also the ones who elect a pope, so Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer participate in the papal election – this falls to a group of 120 "cardinals entitled to vote".
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said there would be a meeting of all cardinals before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as the Consistory, would be held.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce in advance his decision to convene the consistory in February so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from around the world can be scheduled," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinals eligible to vote will likely have dropped by February.
He explained that a pope normally appoints as many cardinals as necessary so that the number of cardinals eligible to vote would again be 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wanted.
Next year's consistory is significant because it is the first since Francis' election in March this year, Valero said.
Currently, there is a certain overhang on the part of Europe and Italy in particular.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of the Council of Cardinals founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything alone.
"Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him," Valero said.
He said it was "quite possible" that Francis would ask the cardinals for advice.
But so far we haven't been in this situation – it's all brand new.
Valero said that typically bishops from large places are called to cardinals, but Francis is "full of surprises – so we don't know who he appoints."
