Is Europe's elite ready to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing business together and defining what those who provide wealth and jobs in the UK want to change in our relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders, asking them what they think about the UK, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed over 1,000 business executives, who roughly represent UK company sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We found that the vast majority of companies now export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing, while states in the EU are stagnating.
They want governments to favour new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than dwelling on the long and arduous process of reforming the EU's obscure institutions.
When asked for their views on specific legal issues – from antitrust to product legislation – the majority of business leaders believe control of these key competencies should be brought back to Westminster.
There was widespread dissatisfaction with the single market, as companies said the cost of Brussels rules now outweighed the benefits of being part of Europe's trade zone – even 40% of large companies, which are traditionally the most pro-European, agreed.
Finally, and this probably says the most, our survey of business leaders found that a clear majority wants Britain to change the deal and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This finding, found in companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that business is pushing for "meaningful change" that will bring the reins of action back to the UK.
There is a lot at stake – a change in the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a change of opinion in favour of remaining in the EU in a referendum at 16 percent.
The Prime Minister should have no doubts: this poll shows that the British economy stands behind his plan to renegotiate the UK's terms for EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a renegotiation to significantly shift the balance of power back to the UK.
A better deal for the UK economy is possible and increasingly necessary now that the eurozone moves towards a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, as the result of our survey shows, which means for businesses an increased focus on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels' approach to regulation.
