General Motors is recalling nearly 19,000 of its all-new 2014 Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickup trucks to address a problem with the manually adjustable seat backrest, according to a statement from the U.S. Vehicle Safety Regulatory Agency on Friday.
On some of the cars, there may be a defect in the mechanism for resetting the front seat backrest.
For this reason, they do not meet the federal guidelines for vehicle safety for head restraints.
"If the vehicle is hit from behind, it is possible that the headrest does not properly protect the occupants, so there is an increased risk of injury," the message read on the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) website.
The recalled models were manufactured between August 1 and September 10.
The delivery of the GM trucks began in June and represents the most important model launch of the leading US automaker since the bankruptcy-related restructuring in 2009.
GM informed vehicle owners of the defect in the first half of October.
The NHTSA was unable to review the notification letter because of the 16-day government shutdown, which negatively impacted car sales in October.
