Kenyan press outraged by controversial media law
"We are in a frightening situation and one may ask oneself: What is stopping parliament from simply abolishing judicial independence tomorrow?" read the newspaper, which considers the bill unconstitutional.
"The law is draconian and very punitive and we oppose it," said Cyrus Kamau, managing director of Capital Group, which owns CapitalFM, one of Kenya's most respected independent radio stations and news websites.
He said the new media tribunal "will always be biased because it is an extension of the government" and restrictions on content and advertising would damage Kenya's position in the global economy.
"I hope the president listens to us and we appeal to him to reject this bill and send it back to parliament," he said.
According to The Star newspaper, the government is "effectively strangling the media" with the new law. By contrast, The Standard writes that democracy and free speech in Kenya have suffered "a severe blow" and called the draft "draconian".
The bill's passage is one of a series of measures aimed at strengthening national security in the wake of the attacks by armed Islamists on the Westgate shopping mall in September.
The Kenyan media drew the ire of the authorities for releasing footage from security cameras showing units sent to the scene allegedly robbing the luxury shopping mall.
Police Chief David Kimaiyo responded by summoning two journalists and a leading media representative to interrogate, although the summons was withdrawn after an outcry from the media.
Under the new law, media houses can be fined up to 20 million Kenyan shillings, and individual journalists can face up to one million and the further risk of losing their professional recognition or being banned from official press accreditation.
The tribunal also has the right to seize the property of the persons concerned if a fine is not paid.
According to the Daily Nation, "even a single penalty can bankrupt most radio stations."
In addition, the newspaper believes that these measures could have a devastating effect on what it describes as Kenya's "vibrant blogosphere".
If they silenced the media, politicians could do whatever they wanted with impunity.
"No one will ever know," wrote Mutuma Mathiu, a journalist with the nation who describes the Kenyan media as a crucial controlling factor in public life.
"If politicians are left to their own devices, they will bankrupt the country and take us back to the time of hunter-gatherers," he commented.
Kenyan legislators have drawn public anger in the past.
In May, they voted to reverse the cuts ordered by the national remuneration commission and reinstated their hefty salaries of about 532,000 shillings per month tax-free – among the highest in the world.
