Court Blocks NYPD Stop and Frisk Policy Decision
A U.S. federal appeals court on Thursday blocked the order of a judge who had called for changes to the New York Police Department's stop-and-frisk program, absolving the judge from the case.
The 2nd U.S. Court of Appeals said Judge Shira Scheindlin's decisions would be suspended until an appeal by the city was decided.
The judge had ruled in August that the city violated the constitution with the way the program for stopping and questioning people was implemented.
The city appealed its assessment and the corrective actions ordered, including the decision to establish a monitoring body to assist the police in changing their policy and training program.
The Court of Appeal heard on Tuesday the arguments for the requested suspension.
The appeal report stated that the judge should be relieved of the case because she violated the Code of Conduct for U.S. judges by stipulating that a judge should avoid the appearance of partiality; this was partly justified by a series of media interviews and public statements in which she had publicly responded to the court's criticism.
The judge had ruled that police officers violated the civil rights of tens of thousands of people because they inappropriately targeted black and Latino men with the stop-and-frisk program.
It appointed an external body to oversee the implementation of significant changes, including policy, training and service oversight reforms, and ordered a pilot program with body-worn cameras in neighborhoods where most checks were carried out.
In August, the city of New York agreed to end the practice of storing the names and addresses of people who were released after being checked by the police.
A hearing on the city's appeal is scheduled after March 14, 2014.
The stop-and-frisk tactic has been criticized by a number of civil rights advocates.
Checks of this kind have been in various forms for decades, but the number of recorded checks during the administration of independent Mayor Michael Bloomberg rose to an all-time high of 684,330 in 2011, most of them black and Latino men.
In 2004, a lawsuit was filed by four men, all of whom belonged to minorities, which developed into a class action.
Proponents of changes to the NYPD's stop-and-frisk program say the changes will end unfair practices and create a more trustworthy and effective police force, as well as affect the way other police headquarters use the scheme.
Opponents argue that the changes will dampen police morale, but not crime; it would also waste money and fail to solve the broader problem of a police force under pressure after the loss of thousands of jobs over the past decade.
The judge pointed out that it did not end the stop-and-frisk practice, which was constitutional, but only reformed the way the NYPD implemented controls.
