Regulations on electronic devices on aircraft remain provisionally in force in Australia
Australian air passengers must continue to turn off tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing, despite efforts in the US to relax regulations on such devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) allows U.S. airlines to change their regulations so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during critical flight phases, provided they are in "airplane mode."
During most of the flight, passengers are already allowed to do so, but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e-books during take-off and landing.
