The decision affects US companies differently depending on the age of the fleet.
They must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from mobile devices and modify manuals, training materials, carry-on baggage programmes and customer instruction.
"After an airline confirms the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any altitude," the FAA said.
