Scientists were able to shed more light on how a dog's tail wagging relates to its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wagged their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), whereas in nervous dogs it was the left side.
Yet now scientists say other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist from the University of Trento, said: "In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain react differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions."
Here we tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right hemisphere is responsible for moving the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail wagging of their conspecifics, the researchers monitored the animals while they watched films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
Probably soon we will understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed the dogs films with dogs – either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog move its tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tilt was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog wagging), their heart rate increased and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience which movements they should and should not worry about.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs and wagging your tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behaviour and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behaviour, then you react on the basis of those experiences."
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their pet's emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert in canine behaviour and a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol's Faculty of Veterinary Science, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when looking at a happy dog.
Another piece of research at the University of Victoria in Canada stated: "Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when its 'tail' wags left rather than right, rather than getting restless – exactly the opposite of the Italian study."
According to him, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
"While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details have yet to be determined – and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior is easy to record, it will probably not take long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
