Pawn shops are booming in Singapore as the crisis has reached the middle class
At a pawn shop in the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay her daughters' school fees.
"My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) every month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand is so great in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is rising – that ValueMax, where it made its swap, became the third pawn shop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pawning jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 Singapore in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawn shops in Singapore charge an APR of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent charged by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawn shops offer the advantage that no creditworthiness or proof of income is required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawn shops as families feel the pressure of rising living costs as well as rising household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit due to loose fiscal policies in developed economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawn shops to make up for the difference in stuttering economies.
This week, rating agency Standard & Poor's cited growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks' creditworthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia relative to gross domestic product, according to the agency.
Malaysia tops the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about high consumer debt in Thailand, which narrowly emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed continued export weakness and a slowdown in consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that with rising costs, people in the middle to low end (of the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," said Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have reinforced the trend of pawning personal belongings as people seize the opportunity to turn the family's jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city-state's 200 pawn shops are gold.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
Thailand's largest pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in customers in its branches in recent months.
The growth in the pawn business is so strong that ValueMax, which operates the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four properties – but also outside Asia, according to yes Lee Ching, managing director of ValueMax.
The company is funding that with 60 percent of the $66 million Singapore it raised this week with its IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire because of high interest rates, yes explains that pawn shops not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly increase debt.
"Customers lend items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables doesn't increase household schooling," she explains.
The pawnbroking business is increasingly accepted by society as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawnbroking are in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax's stores to pawn gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from all walks of life come to us.
"This includes wealthy people who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses that need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow," says yes.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
