Cocaine addicted lawyer who warned drug lord of police investigation must go to prison
Basharat Ditta, 42, passed on information to underworld great Neil Scarborough
The lawyer was afraid that his secret drug addiction might come to light
He was sentenced to three years in prison by Liverpool's Crown Court
A well-known criminal defense lawyer who warned a drug lord about a major police investigation because he feared his secret drug addiction might be exposed was sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, provided underworld figure Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about investigations into his drug trafficking activities after he was compromised by his own cocaine addiction.
Hailed by criminalists as "top-notch," the lawyer, nicknamed "Bash," was arrested at his home in 2011 after police monitored Scarborough, whom he had represented in a previous drug case.
Officials watched as Scarborough, 32, delivered three bags of cocaine to the lawyer's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was at a bar dinner with colleagues.
The investigation revealed that Ditta regularly used Class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Over a period of eight months between January and August 2011, he attempted to obtain unauthorized information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners.
All four suspects were being monitored by police as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
Along with 32 others, they were later arrested after police seized £1.5 million worth of heroin and cocaine and £200,000 in cash during a series of house searches.
Ditta, 42, passed on information to the criminals because he feared his drug addiction could become public.
Today, Ditta, who works for Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn, was found guilty and convicted of two counts of obstruction of justice at Liverpool's Crown Court after a three-week trial.
He admitted cocaine possession in an earlier interrogation.
The lawyer was convicted after police investigated Scarborough to find that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house and put the drugs with a purity of 60 percent in a black golf glove under the lawyer's garbage can.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough regularly telephoned Ditta, who was at dinner at Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park.
The lawyer returned home, got the drugs, and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
In court, it was revealed that Ditta was a "regular user" of cocaine after tests revealed Class A drugs in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied taking cocaine and said he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client, claiming their discussion was subject to "attorney-client privilege."
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were seized and a hair sample was taken from him.
During police interrogation, he stated that he ran an office both at his home address and at work, and that clients would call him at home for legal matters.
In court, it was revealed that he had called key drug trafficking actors, some of whom he had previously represented, after significant arrests and informed them of what investigators knew about them.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said: "A criminal lawyer should know better than anyone else that you are not breaking the law."
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal defence lawyer because he got too involved with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer who supplies drugs to his lawyer.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, because he was the lawyer of these people.
But this went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between lawyer and client.
He counteracted the police investigation as much as possible so that they could continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta thus brought his profession into disrepute.
He was too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any wrongdoing, claiming, "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I'm not, and wanted to pass information to Scarborough, I wouldn't wait 15 hours, I would do it immediately."
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said: "Mr Ditta made the step from a defence lawyer to a criminal the moment he started acquiring drugs from organised criminals."
His cocaine addiction led to a hopeless compromise and made him susceptible to the motives of leading members of organized crime who asked him to gather valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and ensure public trust and confidence.
Ditta has betrayed this trust and tried to entrench himself behind the façade of his profession.
The Lancashire Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation into Ditta, which also resulted in three convictions for possession of cocaine and obstruction of justice, underlining our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We will find you and take you to court.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after pleading guilty of conspiracy to traffick heroin, cocaine and cannabis.
Thirty-five other people involved in drug trafficking were sentenced to a total of 153 years for drug offences.
On his website, Ditta published a Q&A section about himself, stating that his dream job was to represent clients on death row in America as a lawyer, his ultimate dinner guest was Mohammed Ali, and inequality of opportunity was the motivation for his work.
