The completion of this process, which is essentially the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all of Syria's chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Damascus, however, has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and stockpiles.
According to estimates, there are about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve agent sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting was taking place in the city of Safira on Thursday, where experts say there is a chemical weapons production facility and storage facilities, according to the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
The activist group, which tracks the death toll through a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 are civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad's army, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 were Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the death toll in the conflict since March 2011 at 100,000.
This figure has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad's forces have been fighting for weeks in Safira against the rebels, many of whom have links to al-Qaeda groups.
The Observatory said there had been losses on both sides on Thursday, but gave no details.
The fighting underscores the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, as their mission to rid Syria of its toxic arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team is "now convinced that it has seen all the major production and mixing/filling facilities identified by Syria and witnessed their destruction."
Therefore, "no further inspection activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of inspections and visited 21 out of 23 of the sites identified by Damascus.
Due to security concerns, the visit to two facilities was not possible, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, OPWC said the two sites had been "abandoned... and the chemical weapons program objects there had been transferred to other facilities mentioned, which were inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the Safira site was one of the two facilities OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
"I take my hat off to the bravery and courage you have all shown in carrying out the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization," Ahmed Uzumcu, the monitoring organization's director-general, said in a commentary published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting in this civil war against Assad's government and its security forces, to which many members of the Alawites belong, a secession of Shiite Islam.
With regard to further developments, the head of the monitoring group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there had been a powerful explosion at an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
