Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not directly mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair as early as the age of seven or eight?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics' annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are relatively normal among American girls and represent a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually that's not a sign that puberty is coming quickly," Kaplowitz said.
Obvious indications of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, show up earlier in girls.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (occurrence of the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the median age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When breast development begins, it still takes at least two to three years until menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with This Common Problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually constitutes the onset of puberty, but it is considered "precocious" if breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates — something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
With faster progression, tests by an endocrinologist may be indicated to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatment methods to delay early menstruation and ward off another consequence: premature aging of bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the speed of development, the growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication, but he admits, "Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls' feelings of being different from their peers."
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don't want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They're worried about pregnancy risk or how they handle the hygienic side," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter got her days at ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school frightened and excited because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are the cause.
Boys, like girls, enter puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz believes the most compelling premise is the obesity epidemic.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study of girls aged six to nine that established a link between body fat and the onset of puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that play a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards full-scale earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians at the AAP conference underscored the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This can mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than expected.
