What happens to my email on the go?
E-mail actually means electronic letter.
Was the secrecy of correspondence technically implemented in the design of the Internet service e-mail, similar to conventional mail?
In the conception of the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, in the basic technical protocols, no care has been taken to create a stable foundation for a hearing-proof correspondence.
Therefore, a traditional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna's e-mail program or browser sends the mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if she has a GMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses.
On the track, the mail can run through several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are conventional e-mails read on their way through the network?
Most e-mails are read several times by software robots on the go.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam mail, which is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
With systems like GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the e-mails?
The probability that unauthorized persons will read an e-mail is extremely low.
Theoretically, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal means of intercepting or taking note of e-mails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying operations.
Is it possible to protect e-mails against eavesdropping?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against eavesdropping.
With great technical effort, it is also possible to obfuscate the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even easy to recognize who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the email market in Germany?
According to a study by Convios Consulting from August 2013, Yahoo and Google play only a subordinate role in the mainly privately used mailboxes.
While Yahoo-Mail's shares had fallen recently, Google's GMail was able to gain significantly.
