Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA staff charged with sexual offences against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) were charged with sexual offences involving children before allegations were made in 2011 against child care worker Jonathan Lord from Caringbah, the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse learned.
But in the opening statement to the commission, the YMCA had stated that it had "never had anything to do with an incident of child sexual abuse in the organization."
Executive Director Phillip Hare was interviewed about a case in which a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and another in which a physical education teacher at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of abusing children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, a lawyer assisting the commission, that he knew about the first case but did not know the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA's opening statement to the Commission was also inaccurate in claiming that "there had been external reviews of the YMCA recognising the YMCA as at the forefront of child safety".
Rather, evidence before the commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest score out of four possible in a quality audit by the Department of Education and Communities in August of that year.
Hare, who joined YMCA at 21, admitted management failed to hire Lord "from me down" and failed to ensure employees were aware of their obligations to report child safety policy violations.
Lord was convicted earlier this year of sexually assaulting twelve boys during his two years with the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
However, Hare denied that the YMCA had a cultural problem that had prevented staff from reporting Lord's child safety violations.
Staff said they observed violations, including being alone with children, babysitting them privately, letting them sit on his lap, telling one that he loved it, and letting children play with his cell phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who had asked for child protection training because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that Jacqui Barnat, who was Lord's supervisor at the YMCA Caringbah, was "very intimidating and very aloof most of the time".
The managing director stated that he would not accept statements from employees that they did not dare to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, their friendship with Lord had affected their judgment, which is why they did not report him.
Hare stated that he had communicated to the YMCA NSW board of directors his view that the lesson the organisation had to learn from the "Jonathan Lord incident" "did not concern reporting" by employees, and the board had agreed with him.
Hare said the decision to pressure employees to sign confidentiality commitments shortly after the allegations occurred was made by YMCA's Children's Services executive director, Liam Whitley.
He said this was to prevent contamination of the evidence, but this had been "overzealous" and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a safe organisation for children during the period when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert on child sexual abuse, told the commission.
He explained that there had been "serious problems" in recruiting, verifying, inducting, training and supervising staff.
The hearing was adjourned until 20 December.
Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At a length of about 120 meters below Cologne, a sewer from Roman times has been preserved.
If you visit Cologne, you can't miss the cathedral.
The two towers rise about 157 meters into the sky, making it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors who marvel at the two filigree church towers suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne's underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the Cologne Tourism Service Centre directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too big remained of the remains of the old city wall.
Most users of the parking garage therefore rush past the Roman remains today and only park their cars.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal bars in parking deck D2.
You can see ruins about five meters high made of palm-sized stones.
"They are remnants of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century AD," says Schulze.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants take a look into a dark, 15-meter-deep shaft on the upper parking level.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
The next stop on the tour is the Praetorium, where the participants descend back into the depths.
Here we experience the official residence of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the praetor of the CCAA.
A visitor wants to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which means in a good German as much as "city of Roman law and city of the Agrippinensians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the Praetorium is the former governor's palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the vestibule of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here over a length of about 120 meters.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers up the guests.
Schulze still has one surprise.
After fetching the key at the cash register, he leads the group to a 16-meter-deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the mikvah, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to access the groundwater, which was indispensable for the ritual ablutions.
To this day, different water levels can be read in the lower end of the mikvah, whose origins date back to the eighth century, due to changing levels of the Rhine.
The mikvah will become part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is scheduled to begin shortly.
However, it will still be a few years before completion.
