George Kerevan: European unbundling gives Scots a choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport control in Berwick and a barbed-wire border along Hadrian's Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde bill pointed to the potential economic benefits of greater freedom of travel in the rest of Europe, but, as expected, this did not feature in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more convenient for them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued disregard for Brussels would only be a small concession in exchange for what they really want from the Scots.
So not really a story.
And one that is already so old that it already resembles a fossil: The first time I heard the "independence means passport controls" duck was at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance to the European tune?
Why swap the London yoke for Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project has officially died.
Across the EU, parties are gaining ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded just this year, won nearly five million votes in September's federal election, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of Britain's Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is proving to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket into which the respective national economies are forced by sticking to the common currency, many people believe that the European project has gone too far.
The crisis of the euro has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pinned its members to exchange rates that are advantageous for German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave it that way.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself at a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending – spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the "green" energy directives imposed by Brussels – a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen at Grangemouth.
All the world's wage fixing does not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle for keeping Germany in check and raising Paris to par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, which the ailing French economy is struggling with.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a decisive by-election, relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning for Britain's Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split on the right will automatically benefit the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among white French people of the working class?
She wants to use next year's EU elections to forge an anti-EU, anti-single currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and that is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold on to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of ingratiating itself with the US.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can put where.
I suspect Scotland could do quite well in a looser European alliance if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other, like-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider following Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 for rejecting proposed (and made) cuts led by Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to be forced into austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
FAA: Passengers Can Now Use Electronic Devices on Airplanes (but Not Make Cell Phone Calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies from take-off to landing, but can't make phone calls, according to new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the US.
But passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented would depend on the airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated flight crew training manuals and equipment stowage policies to comply with the new regulations.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of wearable electronic devices on aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we may approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when aircraft doors are closed.
They are not allowed to take them off again until the aircraft has reached an altitude of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing approach, passengers must switch it off again and may not take it off again before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices during takeoff, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Association of Professional Flight Attendants, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline on this – both sides will benefit," commented Glading.
We are honestly tired of feeling like watchdogs on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections for surfing, exchanging e-mails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are encouraged to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into airplane mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops still need to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight also remain prohibited.
Regulatory authority for phone calls rests with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA May Lift Ban on Certain Electronic Devices on Takeoff and Landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, safety expert on national transportation issues, told CBS News that cell phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission towers," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to ease restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies say that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore switching off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966 after reports of interference with navigation and communication equipment by passenger-carrying FM radios, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA in such a way that they don't mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi when altitude is reached for several years.
The planes adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit minimal radiation when you turn the page.
But when downloading or sending data, the transfer values are stronger.
One of the advocates of easing restrictions on passengers' device use is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but couldn't find any.
Members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk associated with the use of equipment.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Association of Airline Passengers, said he believed the interference from the devices was genuine, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports from pilots suggesting that aircraft systems were disrupted by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to shut down the devices when landing instruments in poor visibility.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling them a reasonable fit for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that an enjoyable passenger experience is not at odds with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
