Gechingen: No absolute protection possible
"We want to involve the inhabitants in the planning at an early stage," Mayor Jens Häußler opened the citizens' information event on the flood protection concept in Gechingen.
Around 80 participants came to the community hall to have the planned measures explained, to ask questions, to express concerns and to contribute ideas.
Häußler made it clear: "The final decisions are made by the members of the municipal council".
According to Häußler, the flood that caught Gechingen unprepared on 15 May 2009 was a drastic event that raised the question of protective measures for the future.
A river basin study had been commissioned with the neighbouring municipality of Aidlingen, which is now the basis for the flood protection concept in Gechingen.
"The protection of as many built-up plots as possible is the goal," says Häußler.
The planning is based on protection against a flood that is statistically expected every 100 years, according to the German Weather Service.
Climate change is taken into account by a 15 percent surcharge.
In professional circles, this is referred to as "HQ 100aKlima".
The water masses, which had led to considerable damage in Gechingen in 2009, corresponded to a 1000-year flood.
"There is no absolute protection, but we can achieve a relative improvement," says Häußler.
In order to achieve HQ 100aKlima protection, around four million euros must be invested in Gechingen, whereby the municipality can count on state subsidies of around 70 percent.
Häußler pointed out, however, that the funding would only be available if an overall concept was implemented.
For this purpose, the municipality is dependent on the participation of the citizens.
A complex planning and approval procedure had to be completed.
In the best case, implementation could begin in 2016.
Among other things, the protection concept, which was already presented last week in the municipal council (we reported), provides for local measures in the tributary of the river Irm from the Stammheimer valley.
Following the presentation of the flood protection concept, the participants took the opportunity to voice their concerns.
Among other things, it was questioned why more dams and retention basins were not planned to protect the place.
Gregor Kühn, specialist planner of the commissioned engineering office Wald und Corbe from Hügelsheim, who presented the concept, emphasized that it requires the interaction of all the measures presented in order to achieve the desired goal in total.
In addition, one is obliged to find the most economical solution, according to Joachim Wald of Wald and Corbe.
There was resentment among residents of the old town, who even in normal thunderstorms have to suffer again and again from an overload of the sewer network.
The administration is aware of the problem and the first measures have already been taken.
Häußler pointed out, however, that the guidelines for sewer systems were different from those for flood protection and that this should not be mixed.
The municipality is obliged to design the sewer network in such a way that two- to three-year rain events can be absorbed.
Making the sewers larger would cost millions.
