Jumbo manufacturers argue about seat width in the face of large orders
There has been a dispute between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of seats in tourist class on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a bitter clash at this month's Dubai Airshow.
The dispute revolves around the seat width offered to passengers on long flights in economy class – not always the ones airlines strive to achieve, but this designated space is key to the efficiency claims on the latest aircraft from Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week called for an industry standard that mandates a seat width of at least 46 cm (18 inches) in tourist class, but U.S. arch-rival Boeing says airlines should decide.
The controversy comes at a time when aircraft makers are vying to sell even larger versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft and are expecting record orders at the Nov. 17-21 event.
How the rear part of the aircraft is designed – especially whether there are rows with nine or ten seats – is decisive for the stated economic results that the new "mini-jumbo" design is intended to deliver.
Boeing claims its modernized "777X" holds 406 people in tourist class seats that are over 17 inches wide, allowing ten per row.
Airbus says the competing version of the A350 carries 350 people in 18-inch-wide seats in economy class, with nine per row.
Aircraft giants often hand out blows over technical details by means of advertising in the trade press.
Now Airbus is appealing directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to win the race with over 100 orders.
Recently, the company unveiled an ad that could be the start of a new ad war, showing backers a picture of three people squeezed together in a restaurant and titled, "Would you accept that?"
"Boeing is proposing long-haul flights in seats that are narrower than regional turboprops," says Airbus sales chief John Leahy.
With changing eating habits, people are getting fatter, but airplane seats haven't changed radically.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 defined modern long-haul travel, and the end of the century, the weight of the average male American between the ages of 40 and 49 increased by ten percent, according to data from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
The waist circumference of the average male American in the 21st century is 100.8 cm, according to U.S. health statistics.
Airbus says its rival is sticking to a seating concept from the 1950s, when the average body circumference of the newly christened "jet set" was narrower.
According to Airbus, research has been carried out that shows that an additional inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus' figures on seat dimensions, saying it is not up to manufacturers to decide how airlines strike a balance between fares and facilities.
The company also states that according to research, the experience on the plane depends on more than the seat width.
"It really boils down to giving airlines flexibility so they can do what they think they need to do to be successful," said Boeing cabin expert Kent Craver.
They don't want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable.
They know their business better than anyone.
For passengers, it's about more elbow room, but for manufacturers, it's increasingly becoming an issue that can impact sales.
Behind the dispute is a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least $700 billion at list prices in the coming decades, which could have a lasting impact on the export balance of the US or Europe.
As Reuters first reported in July, seat layout is the driving force behind the controversy over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest twin-engine long-haul designs than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing's statements on the results depend in part on comparing the 777X, with its ten seats per row, to the original design of nine seats in the 777.
The increased cost per unit is still lower than currently used machines with ten seats per row.
"Boeing is squeezing more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive with our products," said Kevin Keniston, head of passenger comfort at Europe's Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say full cabins with ten seats per row on existing 777s suggest that many passengers opted for the narrower arrangement, which could come with cheaper airfares.
"Eighteen inches of seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is, from an economic standpoint, the Airbus offering is driven by the threat of the 777," says Mary Kirby, cabin furnishing expert, founder and publisher of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The globetrotting jet sellers even carry tape measure with them to measure the furnishings of the competition.
Even if they advertise comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with high-density designs for budget airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seater rows, but has not yet sold one.
Until recently, Airbus stressed the importance of more cabin adaptability, offering wide aisle seats for some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets, experts say the call for a new industry standard is likely to fizzle out, but could distract from the wave of 777X sales.
