New anti-nicotine vaccine could put an end to smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
More trials are needed before testing in humans, which may take a few more years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results were good.
"We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can one day help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and tried all the methods available on the market, but have found their nicotine addiction stronger than these approaches," Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information to make nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies chase the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from experiencing a nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal activity levels.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, had taken a "time out," the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower, because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if completely safe, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, however, smokers would use it to quit.
"They know that when they start smoking again, they don't feel pleasure because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them break the habit," he explains.
British scientists said the findings were interesting, but warned at the same time that more research was needed.
