Frontier Airlines charges for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 from passengers who want to stow carry-on luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for a piece of carry-on luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, even though Wednesday's announcement said passengers would be allowed to keep the entire can.
The new fee applies to carry-on baggage in the overhead compartment, small bags under the seat are still free.
Frontier said it charges $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 for travelers who pay at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee is aimed at getting travelers to take care of payment upfront.
"We don't want to calculate that sum," she explained.
Airlines began charging for the first and second pieces of checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to circumvent them therefore stuffed as much as possible into their hand luggage, which means that the overhead bins above the seat are often overcrowded.
Fees are one way to encourage passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee isn't really about making money.
It is about the most loyal customers of Frontier, who have clearly expressed that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy their tickets on the airline's website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger may be allowed to carry one piece of baggage free of charge at the Frontier gate, but the next person may have to pay $100 for a comparable bag.
O'Malley said Frontier's website and check-in procedures would be changed so passengers were aware of the fee before they arrived at the gate.
Frontier's new carry-on baggage fee won't come into effect until the summer, and there is no exact date yet.
Passengers often complain about baggage surcharges and other fees, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that transporting the luggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they want it.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage fees as a sign that airlines are making enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
So far, however, most have kept their hands off charges for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for carry-on baggage three years ago, followed later by Allegiant Air, also a low-cost carrier.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungary's Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who is closely following the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that Spirit raised $50 million annually in carry-on baggage charges.
Sorensen, who previously held a senior position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what to expect at the gate if passengers were confronted with the company's unusual carry-on baggage fee.
"The boarding process was one of the smoothest I've experienced in my career in aviation," he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and violent discussions at the gate.
"The plane was full," he explained, "and boarding was running smoothly."
Frontier also follows Spirit on the $2 charged for coffee, tea, soda or juice.
The company explained that passengers who bought soda or juice would be allowed to keep the whole can and coffee would be refilled for free.
Water is still free.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed it seven months later after passengers complained and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier's move to charge carry-on baggage when passengers don't buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to direct customers to its own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies like Orbitz $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This provides all companies with an incentive to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of through an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, the company began awarding only half as many frequent flyer miles when booking through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were shortened again to 25 percent of the flight distance.
A third-party Frontier flight over 1000 miles earns customers only 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats only when purchasing directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but the business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenue fell 9 percent and flight capacity shrank nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to the financial report released Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has been trying to get a grip on Frontier's finances as part of the sale of the company.
