Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Distant planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to start in the next few years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the running.
Distant worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1000 planets near other stars.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, nobody knows.
The choice is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for Earth-like planets and perhaps discover extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions that those responsible at the European Space Agency (ESA) are currently asking.
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that will decisively advance research.
The budget for such "L-missions" is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were up for debate, five of which have now been shortlisted.
Numerous committees review the proposals and follow up with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the scientific program committee.
ESA has selected a total of four major questions to which the missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme, which was initiated in 2007, are to find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes involved in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to investigate this question, the space telescope "Cheops" is to be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity will be examined in more detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could image Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, looking for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, should ultimately shed light on the prerequisites for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation emitted by it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated exemplarily.
With the "Solar Orbiter", ESA has already approved an M-class mission (where the budget is around half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and closely observe the Sun's surface and activity.
Of great interest to researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
To this end, ESA is planning the first of the three L missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme.
The probe "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and will study the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europa, Callisto and Ganymede.
What are the fundamental physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there will also be deviations that could show physicists the way to a new theory under whose roof all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter we are familiar with, which makes up stars, planets and creatures like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy, whose action accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", ESA has already approved an M mission, which is scheduled for launch in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe will investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky and thus enable conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could win the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection procedure.
According to many experts, "E-LISA", an ambitious concept for detecting gravitational waves, has the best chance of being approved as an L-mission.
By this, physicists mean changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission envisages a detector consisting of two or three probes that will be stationed in space.
In contrast to facilities on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves generated during the Big Bang and thus provide new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which will study black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which will detect and study Earth-like planets.
Among other things, proposals for sample return from Mars, for the exploration of the Moon, Venus and asteroids as well as for solar physics have already been rejected.
