Germany is the first European nation to recognize a third gender for children born with ambiguous genitals.
Newborns are no longer rigidly assigned male or female.
Under the new law, parents no longer have to declare gender for such children, but can state "indefinite" or "not fixed" on the birth certificate.
The aim of the law is to take the pressure off parents so that they do not have to make hasty decisions regarding sex assignment operations for newborns and to combat discrimination against intersex people.
An intersex person said years later, according to the BBC: "I am neither man nor woman."
I remain the patchwork created by doctors, mutilated and full of scars.
It is estimated that one in 2,000 children is born each year, neither as a boy nor as a girl.
They belong to the intersex, a group that falls under the diagnosis of "sexual differentiation disorder" (DSD), a collective term for people with atypical chromosomes, gonads (ovaries or testicles) or abnormally developed genitals.
Wallis Simpson may have been intersex.
The understanding of gender identification is still not very well developed, but most experts in the US advise that one should use the best available gender assignment information if a determination is not possible, and not wait for the psychological and physical development of the child before deciding on surgery, if at all.
New York psychiatrist Dr. Jack Drescher, who specializes in gender identification, said the new German law "sounds like a good thing."
Intersex children pose an ethical dilemma.
"Some people have life-threatening conditions that require surgery, but most children don't," he said.
One could make a gender assignment without surgery and then wait and see how the identity develops.
The scientific data on how a child develops his gender identity in the first place is not very accurate.
No one knows why it happens.
It's like the mystery of why people are homosexual.
A 2011 report to the European Commission states that intersex people are to be distinguished from transgender or transgender people because their status is not gender-related, but determined by their biological constitution, which is neither exclusively male nor female, but typically defines both simultaneously or not clearly as one of them.
These characteristics manifested themselves in secondary sexual characteristics such as muscle mass, hair, breasts and stature, primary sexual characteristics such as reproductive organs and genitals, or in chromosome structures and hormones.
The report also provides an overview of the discrimination faced by intersex and transgender people in professional life, as well as the extent of harassment, violence and prejudice.
Boys who do not match the gender image now have a special camp.
Meanwhile, in Australia and Nepal, it is possible for adults to indicate male, female or "third gender" on official documents.
In June, Australian Norrie May-Welby, 52, became the world's first "genderless" person after a court granted lifelong retention of "undetermined" gender status.
In addition to M and W, German ID cards will have a third assignment, X for intersex, according to the Ministry of the Interior.
In neighboring France, gender issues are still controversial, according to a news report on France 24.
In 2011, dozens of French MPs from the staunchly Catholic country signed a petition calling for the "gender theory" to be removed from textbooks.
The US website Catholic Online has also spoken out against the German law, arguing: "When the world is dragged into a new state where gender is a choice but sexual activity is not, then we twist two more pillars of civilization."
The mother of a newborn from Maryland told Baby Zone that she thinks it would be better if babies were assigned a gender at birth.
"Being a parent is stressful enough even without further restrictions, especially if you don't know the gender of your child," she told the parenting website.
Children need stability and security.
Historically, children born with both male and female genitals were called hermaphrodites, after the attractive Greek god who had both sexes.
Just ten years ago, medicine saw gender as something that could be erased and then rebuilt.
But now that the ethical basis of surgery is being questioned, now that it is known how complex gender identity is, and that doctors can also be wrong because they do not know how the child feels when growing up with the gender they assign.
"In the mid-20th century, this was called a 'psychiatric emergency,'" Drescher said.
If such a child was born, then one called not the psychiatrist, but the surgeon.
The prevailing theory about the treatment of children with ambiguous genitals goes back to Dr. John Money of Johns Hopkins University, who argued that gender was malleable.
He coined the term "gender identity" and argued that social and environmental impulses – how parents raise a child – interact with a child's genes and hormones, shaping whether a person considers themselves male or female.
But in a 1966 case known as "John/Joan," his theories became controversial.
He advised the parents of a boy whose penis had been severed during a botched circumcision to castrate the child completely and also remove his testicles and then raise him as a girl.
"Money presented this case as a successful example of a transformation, which it was not," says Drescher.
When the boy was about 15, he switched back to the male sex and married a woman.
At the age of 38, however, he committed suicide.
According to Drescher, there are still doctors who would practice this model.
But in the 1990s, with the advent of the Internet, survivors of these sexual surgeries came forward who are "not happy with the outcome."
For example, Jim Bruce, a 36-year-old author from Montana, who was born with XY male chromosomes but ambiguous genitals.
The doctors were not clear about whether he had a large clitoris or a small penis and were convinced that he could never live a "satisfying life" as a man.
So his external organ and testicles were surgically removed shortly after birth in 1976 and he was raised as a girl.
At the age of 12, he received female hormones.
"I knew I wasn't a girl," he told ABCNews.com
I was unhappy, but it was really hard to ask questions.
At the age of 18, he was to receive a vaginal plasty.
But since he was depressed and knew something was wrong, he demanded his medical records.
What he found was shocking.
I was sterilized when I was born – and no one ever told me that.
Bruce was born with DSD, which prevented his body from producing enough testosterone to develop the genitals.
After learning the truth, he switched back to male identity, received testosterone injections, and had his breasts removed.
As a result of the operation, he has become infertile.
