Rockstar, the consortium that bought the Nortel patents for $4.5 billion, sued Samsung Electronics Co Ltd, HTC Corp, Huawei and four other companies for patent infringement in U.S. District Court in Texas.
Rockstar is jointly owned by Apple, Microsoft, BlackBerry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google is accused of patent infringement in seven cases.
The patents concern technology that matches search terms on the Internet with relevant advertising, according to the lawsuit, which hits the core of Google's search engine business.
Representatives from Samsung, Huawei, HTC and Rockstar could not be reached immediately.
Samsung, Huawei and HTC make phones that work with Google's Android operating system, which is in fierce competition with Apple and Microsoft's mobile products.
In 2011, Google made an initial bid of $900 million for the Nortel patents.
Google increased its offer several times and most recently offered 4.4 billion US dollars.
After being outbid on Rockstar's Nortel patents, Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $12.5 billion, a deal also motivated in part by Motorola's library of patents.
"Although Google failed in its attempt to acquire the patents in suit at auction, Google infringed the patents and continues to do so," the complaint said.
Rockstar is seeking substantial damages from Google for claiming Google's patent infringement was intentional, according to the accusation.
Frankfurt parking fees to rise sharply
Parking in Frankfurt could soon become considerably more expensive.
The magistrate of the city is discussing this morning on a submission by traffic department head Stefan Majer (Greens).
Accordingly, parking fees are to be increased by 50 percent.
However, prices are not to be raised, but the time interval of parking meters and parking ticket machines is to be shortened from 30 to 20 minutes.
In December, the city council has to decide.
The retail committee of the IHK Frankfurt considers this "not a good idea".
The parking possibility directly in front of the shop is "an advantage for smaller specialist dealers that should not be underestimated".
The Verkehrsclub Deutschland is of the opinion that an increase after two decades is "quite appropriate and actually long overdue".
Public transport will also become more expensive.
Oil price continues to fall to USD 96 per barrel
Oil prices continued to fall on Friday after concerns about high supply overshadowed a report that China's energy-hungry manufacturing sector was growing.
The reference crude oil grade for deliveries in December had fallen by 14 cents to USD 96.24 per barrel in electronic trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange in Europe late this morning.
The contract fell 39 cents on Thursday, marking a 5.8 percent drop in October.
The large supply of crude oil has weighed on prices in recent weeks.
The U.S. Department of Energy said Wednesday that U.S. supply increased by 4.1 million barrels last week.
Over the course of five weeks, supply had risen by 25 million barrels.
But on Friday, there were indications of stronger demand from two reports of increased activity in Chinese manufacturing.
This points to a continued recovery of China's economy, which grew to 7.8 percent in the third quarter after hitting its lowest level in two decades in the previous quarter.
Brent crude, a benchmark for international crude also used by U.S. refiners, fell 26 cents to $108.58 a barrel on the ICE Exchange in London.
The throwaway society does not think
The night was long, the music loud and the mood good, but at some point we go home.
Only: In the bellies of the people in the passenger and back seat, the hunger is noticeable.
Sure, one or the other cocktail or sparkling wine may be responsible for this!
What could be more obvious than chilled to the next drive-in to treat yourself to a snack?
I admit, I like to be there when it comes to getting fast food late at night or early in the morning.
A few fries, a coke, a burger - and then nothing like going home and to bed!
But on the way home, the obvious differences between me and other hungry disco-goers become noticeable.
Because what do you have to miss that you throw your fast food bags out of the car window with constant regularity?!
Especially on weekends, discarded paper bags lie on roadsides and in parking lots.
"Why?", I ask myself.
Are people too stupid to take the bags home or to the nearest trash can?
It's not just that the paper stuff spoils the landscape.
Bags have also covered traffic facilities such as crash barriers, causing accidents.
But said "throwaway society" does not think about such a thing, probably it does not even know what this word actually means.
If you are often on the road in the evening, especially with several people in the car, you know what a back seat can look like after nights of partying: clothes, bottles and other garbage pile up there.
A few bags more or less wouldn't matter - in contrast to the street, where nobody wants to trample on the leftovers of others.
I can already see the day coming when the cities and municipalities become too stupid to clear away - and the fast food chains have to demand a deposit for their bags.
Milk and egg alternatives at a glance
Vegan diets require plant-based alternatives to eggs, milk and dairy products.
Pureed tofu with vegetable cream, for example, is a quark substitute.
The Vegetarian Federation mentions others on World Vegan Day on 1 November.
On the occasion of World Vegan Day on 1 November, the German Vegetarian Federation proposes a number of vegan alternatives:
Pure vegetable margarine is a good alternative to butter, yogurt can be replaced by soy yogurt.
Instead of milk, soy, oat, almond or rice milk can be used.
Whippable plant cream replaces conventional whipped cream.
There are also plant-based alternatives to eggs.
Half a crushed, ripe banana, for example, can replace an egg as a binder in a cake.
50 grams of applesauce or a tablespoon of ground flaxseed plus three tablespoons of water are also suitable.
For example, doughs are loosened instead of eggs with a mixture of a teaspoon of baking soda, a tablespoon of cornstarch and three tablespoons of mineral water.
But even 50 grams of soy yogurt or silken tofu can serve this purpose.
According to the Vebu, around 800,000 people in Germany currently eat vegan, i.e. purely plant-based.
A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, believing they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of every car.
The devices, which record every kilometer driven and report the information to the authorities, are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning offices to overhaul the outdated system for financing U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring field of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups, arguing that the government can use the small boxes to record miles driven — and possibly where they were driven — and then use the information to calculate tax assessments.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Liberties Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are not waiting any longer.
They are currently looking at how they can switch to a system where drivers pay per mile over the next decade.
Thousands of motorists have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
"It's not something we're just potentially going to use," said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record miles driven by all California motorists in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded by the taxes Americans pay at the pump, is bankrupt.
But in America, people don't fill up as much as they used to.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state fuel tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 euro cents per liter) has not risen for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax by even one cent when fuel prices are high.
"The gasoline tax just isn't sustainable," said Lee Munnich, an expert on transportation legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mileage-based payment system.
"This is the most sensible alternative in the long term," he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mileage-based user fee.
Not surprisingly, the idea appeals to urban liberals, as the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging exhaust fumes are reduced.
California's planners rely on the system to develop strategies to meet the state's ambitious, statutory climate change goals.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also said he sees this as the most viable long-term alternative.
The independent marketers of the Reason Foundation are also attracted to the idea of making drivers pay according to the distance traveled.
"This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole," explains Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. secretaries of transportation who, in a 2011 report, called on Congress to move toward mileage-based billing.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would have involved 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives blocked the push, responding to the concerns of rural lawmakers representing people who often have to travel long miles to work or the city in everyday life.
Several states and major cities are nonetheless moving in this direction on their own.
The most engaged is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the nation's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the petroleum tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering one.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently exploring how to implement the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, motorists were skeptical at the thought that the government could track their every move.
"Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, director of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
As the test began, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website, "It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into full-blown monitoring devices."
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on individuals' daily movements.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that will allow the state to track miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
This, according to Khan, would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some agencies to a small startup called True Mileage in California.
The company did not originally run to help states tax motorists.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are supposed to pay based on miles driven.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations aren't recorded," said Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can opt for a device with or without GPS.
Or they don't choose a device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to sell the concept to a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than less.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a device for taxation that can also be used to pay parking fees, insurance only for kilometers driven, and to collect real-time speed data from other vehicles that will help drivers avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system," according to a city planning document.
Some traffic planners, however, wonder if all the talk about paying per mile isn't just a huge red herring.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or annual levy could be imposed on motorists with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little petrol, so that they too pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for surgery if one aspirin is enough," explains Randy Rentschler, the Commission's head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists worry about their privacy and many other things.
Bad-Dürrheim: A dream come true for FC
Despite the cold weather and the rain, the official inauguration ceremony for the artificial turf sports field did not lose any of its importance for the city and the football club.
