Snowden ready to "cooperate" with Germany on US surveillance
Edward Snowden, the whistleblower of the US secret service, has declared that he is prepared to travel to Berlin and testify before the German Bundestag if the US National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander do not provide answers about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met Snowden on Thursday in Russia, where he was granted asylum, to discuss the statement in Germany.
In a letter from Snowden, which Ströbele presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, he wrote: "Even though the result of my efforts has been demonstrably positive, my government continues to treat dissent as a breach of loyalty and tries to criminalize political expression with the threat of punishment in which no defense is possible."
But telling the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Snowden writes that he is convinced that the support of the international community can convince the American government to drop the charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
German Interior Minister Hans-Peter Friedrich told Zeit Online: "If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German representatives, then we will find ways to make it possible."
Relations between the US and Germany are strained by allegations that the NSA tapped Chancellor Angela Merkel's cell phone.
Thomas Oppermann, the MP who heads the parliamentary committee responsible for intelligence, said the opportunity should be seized to hear Snowden as a witness if possible "without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the US."
Ströbele, a Green MP, posted a picture of himself and Snowden on his Twitter feed.
He was accompanied on his visit to Russia by two German journalists.
Ströbele explained that, according to the lawyer of former NSA employee, Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Snowden testifies in Germany, then he needs an assurance that he is "safe" there, according to the MP.
Snowden explains in his letter that he faces a "serious and ongoing" campaign of persecution that has driven him from his home.
However, he was touched by the worldwide reaction to "my act of political expression".
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking politicians – including in the United States – have called the revelations about an uncontrolled system of comprehensive surveillance a credit to the general public.
In his letter, Snowden makes an offer of cooperation to the German authorities "when the difficulties surrounding the humanitarian situation have been resolved."
Security concerns grow in Mozambique amid clashes between influential figures
Thousands of people gathered in central Maputo under the watchful eye of the statue of Samora Machel, the founder and first president of Mozambique, to chant calls for peace in a rare public demonstration.
"We want peace again, we want stability," said Vanessa de Sousa, managing director of an investment firm.
Fearing for the country's future, she swapped her business attire for a T-shirt that read "We demand security" in Portuguese and joined the crowd in the capital's Independence Square on Thursday.
For the past two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, some of the worst fighting since the peace agreement more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement, initially supported by white-ruled Rhodesia and later the apartheid government of South Africa in an effort to destabilize the country's independent government.
After the peace treaty of 1992, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe it is unlikely that the country will fall back into full-blown conflict, but recent events have worried foreign investors and locals.
The stakes are high for the fast-growing economy, as the discovery of vast offshore gas deposits and coal deposits in the northwest could attract over $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale of Brazil, Eni of Italy and Anadarko of the United States.
The ruling Frelimo party, the dominant force since 1975, and Renamo blame each other for the tensions.
Renamo claims the government provoked the recent clashes by attacking its members in Sofala province, a traditional stronghold of Renamo, on October 17.
The attacks on the former rebels escalated when government forces attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group's leader, Renamo's spokesman told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for the clashes and accuses the organization of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has tried to downplay concerns about instability.
He told AFP, the French news agency, on Wednesday that Dhlakama considers himself a "loser" who wants to "use all his remaining forces to prove that he can impose his decisions on the government."
Both Frelimo and Renamo stress that they want to avoid war.
But concerns have increased since Mazanga was quoted as saying that Renamo was abandoning the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the FT that he meant that Frelimo no longer respected the agreement.
"Our vision is to resume negotiations and do it seriously," Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to resolve tensions fueled by a series of clashes this year.
"We have two grown men here (Guebuza and Dhlakama) banging their heads together," says Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and Mozambique expert.
None of them is good at negotiating and none is willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo, which is pushing for electoral reforms, has already declared that it will boycott the local elections in November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted the use of force as an attempt by an ailing movement to obtain concessions and financial benefits from the government.
Renamo's electoral success has been declining since 1992, while a newer party, the Movimento Democrático de Moçambique (MDM), founded by a former Renamo member, is expected to improve in the elections.
Mazanga claims that Guebuza – whose resignation is due when his second term ends next year – wants to destroy the country's democracy.
"He doesn't want multi-party democracy, he doesn't want transparent elections, he doesn't want peace because he doesn't want to give up the presidency," Mazanga said.
Renamo's capacity is unclear, but it has launched disruptive attacks on police stations and vehicles on a key north-south route.
Most of the fighting took place in the province of Sofala, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but where Beira is located, the port used by mining companies such as Rio Tinto and Vale to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of the railway for a month after Renamo announced an attack on the line.
Mazanga replied cautiously when asked whether Renamo would repeat this threat.
Renamo wanted to "warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique," Mazanga said.
The instability has added to frustration with the government, says Fernando Lima, head of Mediacoop, an independent media outlet, because many people are already worried about corruption, slow progress in development and a recent wave of kidnapping.
"People think that the government and the president are responsible for the future of the country and he should be the one to find solutions to the problems," he explains.
Omar Sultane, a protester, said people just wanted stability.
"Nobody cares about Renamo and Frelimo, they just want peace and usable roads," he said.
