Chinese newspaper to be "reformed" after call
A front-page Chinese newspaper calling for the release of a reporter accused of defamation should be reformed, a press regulator said.
The Guangzhou-based New Express had printed a rare public call for the release of journalist Chen Yongzhou.
But Chen later admitted on television that he had accepted bribes to falsify reports about a state-owned company.
Now the New Express will undergo a "comprehensive rectification," the regulator said.
The "rectification order" was issued by the Guangdong Department of Press and Publications, Radio, Film and Television.
Preliminary investigations revealed that the New Express, which is part of the Yangcheng Evening News Group, had published several inaccurate reports about the listed company Zoomlion between September 2012 and August 2013.
"The editorial management of the New Express was disorderly," the regulator said in a statement.
She said they had decided to "impose an administrative penalty on Chen Yongzhou and revoke his reporter's license."
In addition, "the Yangcheng Evening News Group was instructed to carry out a full rectification of the New Express and recommended that the relevant New Express officials be identified and the New Express leadership team be reviewed without delay."
Chen had written several articles for the New Express, reporting alleged financial irregularities at a construction equipment manufacturer called Zoomlion.
After he was arrested, the newspaper published two front-page appeals for his release and backed his journalistic work.
But then Chen appeared on state television and admitted that he had published false reports in exchange for payment.
"In this case, I harmed Zoomlion as well as the entire news industry and its ability to gain the public's trust," he told state news channel CCTV.
I did it primarily because I was after money and fame.
I realized that I did the wrong thing.
Following Chen's apology, the New Express published a front-page apology, saying it had failed to properly verify the reports.
