Haslach: Skepticism is visibly giving way to confidence
With the elections to the parish council in 2015, for example, fundamental changes will change in the pastoral care unit Haslach (SE).
There will then be only one common parish council for all six parishes.
In a joint meeting on Saturday, the committees from Haslach, Hofstetten, Mühlenbach, Fischerbach, Steinach and Welschensteinach prepared for the changes.
Because the fundamental decisions of the diocese can no longer be changed and it is up to the parish councils to implement them as satisfactorily as possible.
In the course of the day it became particularly clear: the scepticism towards the new is hesitantly but visibly giving way to confidence.
The extremely constructive discussions of the six committees with the full-time employees of the pastoral care team ranged from the ideas and expectations of the innovations in 2015 to concrete proposals about the future composition and size of the parish council.
Regional Dean Georg Schmitt explained the revised guidelines for pastoral care units in the Archdiocese of Freiburg on the basis of a presentation.
According to this, the SE Haslach as a parish will in future form a corporation under public law, which will assume the rights and obligations of the six individual parishes.
There will only be a joint parish council and a board of trustees, in which the pastor is represented by virtue of his office.
At least two elected members from each parish should be represented, in the six parishes so-called parish teams are formed locally.
In the future, its task will be to promote church life in the village.
On the question of the finances of the individual parish, there was then a considerable need for discussion.
The changes stipulate that accumulated assets in the parishes will be retained for a specific purpose.
The liabilities, on the other hand, are transferred to the entire municipality.
Especially with regard to the large planned investments, the obligation of which then affects all parishes, there were great concerns.
"Even in the past, investments were only made in projects that could be managed by the individual parishes alone," said Haslach's parish council chairman Bruno Prinzbach.
Barbar Ritter, chairwoman of the committee in the pastoral care unit Schutterwald-Neuried, described practical experience with a joint committee for five parishes.
In 2006, they had set themselves the task of "becoming one, staying five" and had to realize that this is not so easy.
The committees of the Haslach pastoral care unit then set about answering questions about the future composition and size of the joint parish council as well as the practical work of the parish teams.
The elaborations will be substantiated in further meetings and decided at a further joint meeting of all six bodies next spring.
At the end, parish councillor Michael Schöner from Steinach presented the new logo of the pastoral care unit, which was approved by a clear majority.
