An Obama voter's cry of despair
I voted for President Obama twice, hoping that change was possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by Republican blockade tactics.
The blockade policy does not excuse Obamacare's website problems, the drone strikes
Obama's memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what would have been possible.
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a terribly sad book.
It's a book that I thought would cheer me up and give me hope again during the gloomy second year of my medical school.
It is called "The Audacity to Win" and describes Barack Obama's memoirs of the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish my patient transcripts in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take a speech away.
The election turned into a landslide victory, and news anchors paused to recall the historic significance of that hour.
My classmates cried with joy and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on its way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a rude awakening, like being torn out of a dream.
It's hard to remember those optimistic times – they seem like a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first voted, something has actually changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and multifaceted things Obama has accomplished, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that partisan blockade tactics have overturned too many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times to colleagues and acquaintances, I have reached the end of my attempts at explanation.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it allows the wiretapping of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on Americans' private lives and why whistleblowers who expose government misconduct are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the findings of a report that said the White House's efforts to silence the media were the "most aggressive... since the Nixon administration".
And recently, it can't excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that the work of government could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the office of MP is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre dominate the public debate.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely chosen by the government itself.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was thrilled with his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and half-baked alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had been hearing about for so long.
But with Obama's approval ratings dropping below 45% this week, this book has made the return to 2008 all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week, I read a passage in the book describing how Obama suffered a heavy loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with election workers after the decision, he told his staff they needed to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to find our magic again," he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree with you more.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
