For more than 30 years, Josef Winkler has been writing the hardships of his childhood and youth from the soul.
The catastrophes of his Catholic village childhood - the speechlessness, the tendency to brute force and blunt sexuality, the narrowness and joylessness - have been described many times by the Carinthian poet.
The Büchner Prize winner is known above all as a prose author, theatre texts are rare in his work.
Collage of prose texts Gerhard Fresacher has therefore put together a collage of prose texts for his performance "Wetterleuchten auf der Zungenspitze", which can now be seen in Garage X on Petersplatz.
The theatre-maker combines elements from the autobiographical novel "Der Leibeigene" (1987) with prose miniatures from "Leichnam, seine Familie belauernd" (2003).
On the largely empty stage - an important prop: a crumpled sofa, on which copulating and masturbating are hinted at - the eight-member ensemble maneuvers through the text material.
Director Fresacher seems to trust the text little.
The 70-minute performance whitewashes the original with a wealth of directorial ideas, known from the repertoire of post-dramatic forms of play.
Especially the actresses get their turn in the sometimes somewhat questionable scenic implementations.
They are touched hard, dipped with their heads under water, stapled to the wall with their evening robes.
Squeezed into cellophane or bodice, they trudge through the production on dangerously high sticks, either monologue loudly or lie completely silent on the stage floor.
However, the text hardly conveys itself in this strained way.
The best moments of the evening are when there is singing - the spectrum ranges from Deep Purple to folk songs.
Only towards the end does the exaggerated performance calm down a bit, and Winkler's downright absurd humor flashes up.
